	<fdd:sustainabilityFactors>
		<fdd:disclosure>AVI is fully documented and a proprietary file format developed by Microsoft and IBM as part of <a href="https://www.loc.gov/preservation/digital/formats/fdd/fdd000025.shtml">RIFF</a>, the Resource Interchange File Format for Windows 3.1. FFV1 is an open-source specification and comes from the <a href="http://ffmpeg.org/">FFmpeg</a> project.</fdd:disclosure>
		<fdd:documentation>See <fddLink id="fdd000059">AVI</fddLink>. The FFV1 <a href="http://www.ffmpeg.org/~michael/ffv1.html">specification</a> is maintained by the FFmpeg project&apos;s current leader Michael Niedermayer. </fdd:documentation>
		<fdd:adoption>Modest adoption of <fddLink id="fdd000059">AVI</fddLink> and <fddLink id="fdd000341">FFV1</fddLink> in heritage repositories. One notable adopter of the AVI/FFV1 combination is the <a href="https://www.mediathek.at/">Austrian Mediathek</a>. Information about their use of FFV1 can be found <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160417021816/http://www.dva-profession.mediathek.at/documentation/2-dva-profession-used-at-the-austrian-mediathek/">here (link available through Internet Archive)</a>.</fdd:adoption>
